1️⃣ Developer & Test Team Coordination
Strong collaboration between Development and Testing teams was critical in managing the highly complex streaming data architecture.
All development team members proactively addressed issues in real time, reducing turnaround time and preventing downstream impact.
This close coordination significantly improved stability and confidence before go-live.

2️⃣ Automation Framework & Data Quality Monitoring
The automation framework developed by the Testing team enabled proactive monitoring and immediate data quality validation post go-live.
It provided strong visibility for Application Support teams to quickly assess issues and system health.
The solution was well appreciated by the Central Data Quality Governance team for strengthening control and transparency.


1️⃣ Clarity on Test Phase Dependencies
We identified the need for clearer articulation of dependencies between Component Link Testing and E2E testing phases.
Ambiguity around test data ownership and readiness created avoidable confusion and sequencing challenges.
Going forward, formal dependency mapping and entry/exit criteria must be agreed upfront.

2️⃣ Better Use of Test Data Across Phases
Test data generated during Component Link Testing was not optimally leveraged for downstream Unit and E2E preparation.
Clear guidance on how test outputs feed subsequent phases would improve efficiency and reduce rework.
Establishing a structured data handover model will strengthen overall test execution.

3️⃣ Dependency Governance in Complex Streams
In a highly complex streaming ecosystem, making one phase a hard dependency without full impact assessment increased risk.
Dependency decisions should be collaboratively validated across Dev, Test, and Business stakeholders.
Stronger governance on phase gating will improve predictability and delivery confidence.
